    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1458603649" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1458603649" />
    <a title="Cara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7257887-cara"><img alt="Cara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1379980621p2/7257887.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1458603649?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cara" href="/user/show/7257887-cara">Cara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1458603649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3539492657061712096">Spoiler: the endings are all happy in these stories. Love wins. The characters are lovable and humorous in their caricature imperfections, and they always forgive each other for those over-the-top imperfections. I should probably look down on this book for it&apos;s predictability and its obvious patterns that make the end of the last few stories completely predictable. Instead, I find it comforting. Like grilled cheese and tomato soup on a winter afternoon. <br/><br/>Although I&apos;m old enough to know that there</span>
  <span id="freeText3539492657061712096" style="display:none">Spoiler: the endings are all happy in these stories. Love wins. The characters are lovable and humorous in their caricature imperfections, and they always forgive each other for those over-the-top imperfections. I should probably look down on this book for it's predictability and its obvious patterns that make the end of the last few stories completely predictable. Instead, I find it comforting. Like grilled cheese and tomato soup on a winter afternoon. <br /><br />Although I'm old enough to know that there isn't any such thing as happily-ever-after (and I think Montgomery isn't exactly promising there is--all of her characters are too human to stay perfectly happy forever,) I still want to escape to that world every so often. I still want to believe that what makes us odd is what makes us wonderful. I still want to think that opposites attract and that mistakes can and will be forgiven. <br /><br />I read these to myself as bedtime stories for sweet dreams. I wish I could be L. M. Montgomery's niece. Or better, her character. I'm sure she'd describe me in a way that would make me lovable, even to myself, even on my worst days. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3539492657061712096" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

